 the Napoleonic wars to reduce the possibility of recurrence, which first institutionalized the practice of jointly managing the balance of power. Through the Concert’s many successes, she shows that the words and actions of state leaders in public forums contributed to collective self-restraint and a commitment to problem solving—and at a time when communication was considerably more difficult than it is today. Despite the Concert’s eventual breakdown, the practice it introduced—of face to face diplomacy as a mode of joint problem solving—survived and is the basis of global governance today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConcert of Europe. 0aInternational cooperationxHistoryx19th century. 0aInternational cooperationxHistoryy19th century. 0aInternational relationsxHistoryx19th century. 0aInternational relationsxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic relations and politicsxHistoryx19th century. 0aPublic relations and politicsxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorld politicsx19th century. 0aWorld politicsy19th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226060255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226060255.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles